<br>
This code is already present in the game, so this would not be a problem.  Have you ever been in a group fighting at the giant fort in FM when some lame kiting dr00d shows up with his 3/4ths dead giant and starts /yelling for help?  Have you been in the situation where your group doesn't act fast enough to save that druid and he ends up taking a dirtnap courtesy of one angry beat-up giant?  Has your group ever finished the kill after that?<br>
<br>
The code is there so that you can get XP/looting rights from a mob regardless of what its starting HP is, be it full or .00001%.  Since you drop off the hate list when you zone (and I'd assume your other traits go with that - total damage done, current hate, etc.) I believe the way they calculate it for mobs currently is:<br>
<br>
1) Group all people on the hate list based upon in-game groupings (ie. if Player1 and Player2 were in the same group, and both on the hate list, then their damage totals are combined)<br>
2) Compare total damage tallies from all groups represented on the hate list.<br>
3) Provide XP/looting rights to the group with the highest damage tally<br>
<br>
<br>
This system would work fine for PvP calculations as well.  It would just mean quite a bit of extra effort in adapting the code, as well as significant system requirements (as I addressed before), but it's not a new approach that would require coding from scratch.<br>
<br>
Digits<br>
<br>
ps.  this is why in a multi-group situation attacking a single mob, if team-members die, the group that did the most damage doesn't necessarily get the kill.  This is because the group loses the damage tally from everyone who died, and are only credited for the damage done by the people left standing....and as we all know, if you're doing the most damage to a mob, there's a good chance you won't be standing when that mob falls :P<br>
